			<p>The test for the gene related to Alzheimer&rsquo;s can usually tell you if you are more likely than others to develop Alzheimer&rsquo;s Disease. The test may detect if you have an increased chance of getting the disease, <span class="highlight">but it cannot predict whether you will get the disease</span>&mdash;or whether you won&rsquo;t. In this section we explain the test and what you can learn from it.</p>
			<h3>About Gene Tests</h3>
			<p>In general genetic tests look for variations in genes that, when present, can lead to an illness or raise one&rsquo;s chances of developing an illness. Genetic tests are done on small amounts of saliva or blood or by swabbing the inside of the mouth.</p>
			<h3>Alzheimer&rsquo;s and the APOE Gene</h3>
			<p>Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease can be caused by genes, non-inherited factors, or some combination of both. There is one gene that has been associated with late-onset Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease. It is called the <span class="highlight">Apolipoprotein E</span> gene&mdash;or APOE for short.</p>
			<p>The APOE gene has three forms: e2, e3, and e4. The e4 form is the one which is associated with a higher risk of Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease. The genetic test can tell which form or forms of the gene are present. A person can have zero, one or two e4 genes.</p>
			<p>If you have one copy of the e4 gene, the risk for developing Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease increases and two copies makes the risk higher. Research is ongoing so we don&rsquo;t know the exact increased risk but currently, it is believed to be as follows.</p>
